  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 29.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And changed his prison garments.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The subject to \"changed\" may be either \"Jehoiachin\" or\" Evil-Merodach.\" Our translators preferred the latter, our Revisers the former. In either case the general meaning is the same. Evil Merodach supplied suitable garments to the released monarch instead of his \"prison garments,\" and Jehoiachin arrayed himself in the comely apparel before taking his seat among his equals. Dresses of honor are among the most common gifts which an Oriental monarch makes to his subjects (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 41:42",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 6:8, 11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 8:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 5:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Xen., 'Cyrop.,' 5:1. § 1). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Jehoiachin - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "did eat bread continually before him.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Besides giving occasional great feasts (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 1:3-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), Oriental monarchs usually entertain at their table daily a large number of guests, some of whom are specially invited, while others have the privilege of daily attendance (see ' Ancient Monarchies,' vol. 3. pp. 214, 215). It was to this latter class that Jehoiachin was admitted. Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 9:7-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which shows that the custom was one not unknown at the Jewish court. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "All the days of his",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Jehoiachin's - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "life.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Jehoisohin enjoyed this privilege till his death. Whether this fell in the lifetime of Evil-Merodach or not, is scarcely in the writer's thoughts. He merely means to tell us that the comparative comfort and dignity which Jehoiachin enjoyed after the accession of Evil-Merodach to the throne was not subsequently clouded over or disturbed. He continued a privileged person at the Baby-Ionian court so long as he lived. 2 Kings 25:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "\"And he (Jehoiachin) changed his prison garments,\" i.e., took them off and put other regal clothing on (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 41:42",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). \"And ate continually before him all his life,\" i.e., ate at the king's table (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 9:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Moreover a daily ration of food was supplied to him by the king for the maintenance of his retainers, who formed his little court. The חיּיו כּל־ימי of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 25:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", upon which Thenius throws suspicion without any reason, refers to Jehoiachin like that in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 25:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; for the historian intended to show how Jehoiachin had fared from the day of his elevation to the end of his life. At the same time, we cannot infer from this with any certainty that Jehoiachin died before Evil-merodach; for the favour shown to him might be continued by Evil-merodach's successor. We cannot make any safe conjecture as to the motives which induced Evil-merodach to pardon Jehoiachin and confer this distinction upon him. The higher ground of this joyful termination of his imprisonment lay in the gracious decree of God, that the seed of David, though severely chastised for its apostasy from the Lord, should not be utterly rejected (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 7:14-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). At the same time, this event was also intended as a comforting sign to the whole of the captive people, that the Lord would one day put an end to their banishment, if they would acknowledge that it was a well-merited punishment for this sins that they had been driven away from before His face, and would turn again to the Lord their God with all their heart.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]